tables.NBA and Euroleague (since 2019): NBA basketball courts have a 16 ft m rectangular key. Hash marks in an arc mark the portion of the circle for jump balls at the free throw line. Keys may have both NBA and NCAA or NAIA marking to allow use of the same floor by both organizations.  Euroleague, which uses a 4.9 m ft rectangular key, reinstated the NBA rule on jump balls in 2019.
tables.NCAA, NAIA, NFHS (U.S.): NCAA, NAIA, and NFHS basketball courts have a 12 ft m wide key. The free throw lane has no hash marks because jump balls are not held at the free throw line.
tables.FIBA (since 2010): Since 2010, all FIBA-specification courts have used 4.9 m ft rectangular keys. Some competitions, however, use the NBA-specification key.
tables.FIBA (until 2010): Prior to 2010, FIBA-specification courts had trapezoidal keys that were 6 m ft at the baseline and 3.6 m ft at the free throw line. The jump-ball circle was marked with solid lines on both sides of the free-throw line, the inside of which was often used for sponsor advertising.
